<exercise checkit-seed="0006" checkit-slug="SQ5" checkit-title="Basic convergence tests">
    <statement>
        <p>
            For each of the following series, use the <em>Divergence</em>, <em>Alternating Summation</em> or <em>Integral</em> test to determine if the series converges.
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{3 \, n^{5} + 4 \, n^{3}}{3 \, n^{5} + 2 \, n^{4} + 2 \, n + 3}.</m>
            </li>            
            <li>
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{n}.</m>
            </li>            
            <li>
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{5 \, \left(-1\right)^{n} n^{2}}{4 \, n^{3} + 4 \, n + 1}.</m>
            </li>            
        </ol>
    </statement>
    <answer>
       <ol>
            <li>
                
                        <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{3 \, n^{5} + 4 \, n^{3}}{3 \, n^{5} + 2 \, n^{4} + 2 \, n + 3}</m> diverges by the <em>Divergence</em> test.               
                   
                
            </li>            
            <li>
                
                        <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{n}</m> diverges by the <em>Integral</em> test.               
                   
                
            </li>            
            <li>
                
                        <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{5 \, \left(-1\right)^{n} n^{2}}{4 \, n^{3} + 4 \, n + 1}</m> converges by the <em>Alternating Summation</em> test.                
                   
                
            </li>            
        </ol>
    </answer>
</exercise>
